            <fr:addr>jms-00RN/13</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-00RN-13.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Baby steps in higher domain theory › the Phoa principle vs. synthetic quasicoherence"><fr:link href="jms-00RN.xml" title="Baby steps in higher domain theory" addr="jms-00RN" type="local">Baby steps in higher domain theory</fr:link> › the Phoa principle <html:em>vs.</html:em> synthetic quasicoherence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>The higher Phoa principle is a Kock–Lawvere / <html:em><fr:link href="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh.xml" title="A general Nullstellensatz for generalized spaces" addr="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh" type="local">“synthetic quasi-coherence”</fr:link></html:em> axiom that comes directly from the geometric theory of a strict interval, as a quotient of the theory of bounded distributive lattices (<fr:link href="danielgratzer.xml" title="Daniel Gratzer" addr="danielgratzer" type="local">Gratzer</fr:link>).</html:p>
            <html:p><html:strong>Question.</html:strong> What are the other domain theoretic consequences of synthetic quasicoherence?</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>9</fr:month>
              <fr:day>12</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:addr>jms-008U</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-008U.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Spectrum of an algebra">Spectrum of an algebra</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Definition 4.6 of <fr:link href="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh.xml" title="A general Nullstellensatz for generalized spaces" addr="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh" type="local">Blechschmidt</fr:link></fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> be a geometric theory and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex> be its generic model in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {Set}{\mathopen {}\left  [\mathbb {T}\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. The <html:em>spectrum</html:em> of a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>-algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is the set of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>-algebra homomorphisms <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M\to U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>. (Recall that a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>-algebra is a model of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> equipped with a homomorphism from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>.)</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
        <fr:tree show-metadata="true" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false">
          <fr:frontmatter>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>
                <fr:link href="jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
              </fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2023</fr:year>
              <fr:month>9</fr:month>
              <fr:day>12</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:addr>jms-008T</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>jms-008T.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Synthetic quasicoherence">Synthetic quasicoherence</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Theorem 4.10 <fr:link href="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh.xml" title="A general Nullstellensatz for generalized spaces" addr="blechschmidt-2023-qcoh" type="local">Blechschmidt</fr:link></fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> be a horn theory. The generic <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex>-model <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex> is <html:em>quasicoherent</html:em> in the following sense: internal to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {Set}{\mathopen {}\left  [\mathbb {T}\right  ]\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, for any finitely presentable <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>-algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, the canonical <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U_{\mathbb {T}}]]></fr:tex>-algebra homomorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \to  U_{\mathbb {T}}^{\operatorname {Spec}{A}}]]></fr:tex> sending <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda  f:\operatorname {Spec}{A}. f\,a]]></fr:tex> is an isomorphism, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Spec}{A}]]></fr:tex> is the <fr:link href="jms-008U.xml" title="Spectrum of an algebra" addr="jms-008U" type="local">synthetic spectrum</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
